equation_narrative.headline: Model misreads flexible loop position as small hydrophobic, missing proline's structural constraint
equation_narrative.story: Position 38 sits in a flexible loop (KEGIP[P]DQQRL) with 6 structural contacts but no co-evolutionary signal. Through L23, the model assembles a representation consistent with small, flexible residues—the logit lens fluctuates between hydrophobic (L, A, V) and polar (S) amino acids as the model reads local sequence and structural neighbors. The representation remains chemically ambiguous through the perception phase. At L24-27, the decision phase begins: alanine-specific prediction channels activate strongly, while proline support builds more slowly. By L29-32, a dramatic competition unfolds—valine surges to 40% at L28, proline peaks at 36% at L31, but alanine ultimately wins at 43% through sustained MLP support in the final layers. The model correctly identifies the flexible, non-bulky character of the position but fails to recognize the backbone constraint that uniquely favors proline.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 show the model reading a structurally ambiguous context. Six structural contacts provide limited chemical information—no strong hydrophobic core or charged surface signature emerges. The absence of co-evolutionary signal (0 coupled positions) indicates this is not a functionally constrained site. Early attention (L1-9) establishes local sequence context, with features F1:5480 and F9:5728 (both 45-57 proj) encoding the surrounding charged residues (K, E, D, Q). The logit lens oscillates through 18 lead changes in L1-23, alternating between small hydrophobics (A, L, V) and polar residues (S, T)—this reflects the model building a representation of a flexible, non-bulky position rather than committing to a prediction. By L18, attention features F18:4071 (18.3 proj) and F18:1860 (17.8 proj) encode the loop environment. The representation character remains 'small and flexible' without strong chemical specificity.
perception_phase.context_character: Flexible loop environment with mixed local chemistry (flanked by charged K, E, D, Q residues). Six structural contacts provide modest constraints but no dominant hydrophobic or polar signature. No co-evolutionary coupling indicates limited functional constraint.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 6 residues within 8Å, read primarily at L8 (head 6, -1.63 proj eraser) and L26 (head 6, -2.07 proj structural eraser)
Local sequence: Strong attention to flanking charged residues (K36, E37, D39, Q40) throughout L1-23, encoded in F1:5480, F9:5728 features
Loop flexibility: F18:4071 (18.3 proj) and F18:1860 (17.8 proj) encode secondary structure—absence of helix/sheet constraints
No co-evolutionary signal: 0 coupled positions, indicating this site is not under strong functional selection

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes at L24-33 through intense MLP-driven competition. Alanine gains early momentum at L24 (F24:5080 with 37.2 proj) and receives sustained support from MLP neurons through L29-32 (total +7.8 delta at L29, +5.1 at L32). Valine surges dramatically at L27-28, peaking at 40% (L28 MLP: +6.9 total proj), driven by hydrophobic-voting neurons. Proline builds steadily from 9% at L23 to 36% at L31, supported by proline-specific neurons N31:5095 (1.20 proj) and N28:1320 (0.74 proj), but loses ground in the final layers. Alanine's victory comes from consistent small-residue prediction channels (F30:7623, F30:5728, F33:9048 with 81.3 proj) that favor its minimal side chain over proline's cyclic constraint.
decision_phase.transition: At L23-24, the representation shifts from context-encoding to candidate-specific prediction. F24:5080 (37.2 proj, attention) is the first strongly amino-acid-specific feature, marking where perception becomes decision. MLP L24 contributes +1.73 total projection with neurons N24:1185 (0.68 proj for P), N24:3615 (0.61 proj for P), and N24:1483 (0.55 proj for P) casting the first decisive votes.

candidates.narrative: Alanine emerges as the winner through sustained decision-phase support from L24-33. At L24, F24:5080 (37.2 proj) activates as an alanine-favoring attention feature. MLP neurons consistently vote for small residues: N29:3539 (0.40 proj for P but also supports small AAs), N30:4443 (0.74 proj, votes R/T/P), and critically N31:5095 (1.20 proj, votes A>P). The final layer features F33:9048 (81.3 proj) and F33:2787 (74.1 proj) strongly favor alanine's minimal side chain. Alanine rises from 21% at L23 to 43% at L33, winning because the model interprets 'small and flexible' as 'minimal side chain' rather than 'backbone constraint.'
key_evidence: F24:5080 (attn, 37.2 proj) — early alanine-specific prediction channel
N31:5095 (1.20 proj) — votes A (1.39) > P (1.20), favors small residues
MLP L29: +7.0 delta, MLP L32: +5.8 delta — sustained small-residue support

candidates.narrative: Serine is the runner-up at 23%, reflecting the model's recognition of the position's polar-compatible character. Serine leads the logit lens at L0 (22.6%) and remains competitive through L17-21, indicating the representation initially encodes polar flexibility. In the decision phase, serine receives support from polar-voting neurons but loses ground at L29 (drops to 3.3%) before surging back at L33. The late recovery suggests final-layer features F33:2787 (74.1 proj) and F33:6423 (71.4 proj) encode a 'small polar or hydrophobic' preference that includes serine as a viable alternative to alanine.
candidates.key_layers: Early leader L0-17, recovers at L33
key_evidence: Logit lens: 22.6% at L0, reflects initial polar-flexible representation
L29 suppression: drops to 3.3% as hydrophobic channels dominate
L33 recovery: rises to 22.7%, final features allow small polar residues

candidates.narrative: Proline is the correct answer but ranks third at 13.5%. It builds support slowly from 0.09% at L0 to 9.3% at L23, then accelerates in the decision phase, peaking at 36% at L31. Proline-specific neurons activate strongly: N21:1111 (0.51 proj), N28:1320 (0.74 proj), and N31:5095 (1.20 proj, though it votes A>P). MLP L28 provides massive proline support (+6.9 total proj), and N30:4443 (0.74 proj) votes for backbone-constrained residues. However, proline loses the final competition because the model's representation emphasizes 'small side chain' over 'cyclic backbone constraint'—the features that fire most strongly at L33 favor minimal-volume residues (A, S) rather than conformationally restricted ones.
key_evidence: N28:1320 (0.74 proj) — proline-specific neuron, votes P > D > Q
N31:5095 (1.20 proj for P) — strong proline vote, but also votes A higher
MLP L28: +6.9 total proj, massive proline support wave
Peak at L31: 36%, but loses to alanine's sustained final-layer advantage

candidates.narrative: Valine is a dramatic contender, surging from 6% at L23 to 40% at L28 before collapsing to 8% at L33. This surge is driven by hydrophobic-voting MLP neurons at L27-28: the model briefly interprets the structural contacts as favoring a small hydrophobic core residue. However, attention at L28 (head 8, +1.96 proj structural writer) and L29 (head 18, -1.71 proj structural eraser) revise this interpretation, and valine loses support as the model recognizes the position is not in a tightly packed hydrophobic environment. The valine trajectory illustrates the model's mid-decision uncertainty about whether the position requires hydrophobic packing or just minimal volume.
key_evidence: L28 peak: 39.6%, driven by hydrophobic MLP neurons
L28 attention head 8 (+1.96 proj) — structural writer briefly favors hydrophobic
L29 attention head 18 (-1.71 proj) — structural eraser suppresses valine
Collapse L29-33: drops to 7.6% as model rejects hydrophobic-core interpretation

candidates.narrative: Leucine dominates the logit lens from L2-L11, peaking at 25% at L11, but this reflects the representation's hydrophobic-leaning character during early perception, not a model prediction. Leucine appears because early features (F1:5480, F9:5728) encode the local sequence context, and the structural contacts being read at L8-12 include some hydrophobic residues. The model is assembling a representation of 'what's nearby' rather than 'what should go here.' Leucine fades after L11 as the model refines its understanding that the position requires flexibility rather than hydrophobic bulk, and it never re-emerges in the decision phase.
key_evidence: Logit lens: peaks 24.6% at L11, reflects hydrophobic-leaning representation
Early structural reading: L8 head 6 (-1.63 proj) reads hydrophobic contacts
Fades by L17: drops to 13%, never recovers in decision phase

turning_points.description: The representation oscillates rapidly between hydrophobic (L, A, V) and polar (S, Y) character as the model reads structural contacts and local sequence. Eighteen lead changes occur, with leucine dominating L2-L11 (peaking at 25%). This is not indecision—it's the model assembling a multi-faceted representation. Attention heads read structural neighbors (L8 head 6, -1.63 proj), while early features F1:5480 and F9:5728 encode the charged local context (K, E, D, Q). The logit lens reflects the chemical diversity of the information being integrated, not candidate preferences.

The perception-to-decision transition occurs here. At L23, the representation is still context-encoding (alanine at 21%, serine at 13%, proline at 9%). At L24, amino-acid-specific prediction channels activate: F24:5080 (37.2 proj) favors alanine, and MLP L24 contributes +1.73 total projection with proline-voting neurons N24:1185, N24:3615, N24:1483. By L25, the model has committed to a 'small residue' decision space, and the competition narrows to A, S, P, V. This is where the running_predictions shift from 'representation character' to 'actual candidate probabilities.'

The decisive competition unfolds. Valine surges to 40% at L28 (MLP +6.9 total proj) as hydrophobic neurons fire, but attention heads L28:8 (+1.96 structural writer) and L29:18 (-1.71 structural eraser) revise this, and valine collapses. Proline builds steadily, peaking at 36% at L31 with strong support from N28:1320 (0.74 proj) and N31:5095 (1.20 proj). Alanine maintains consistent support throughout (L29 MLP +7.0, L32 MLP +5.8). The final outcome is determined by which interpretation of 'small and flexible' wins: alanine's 'minimal side chain' beats proline's 'backbone constraint' because the most active final-layer features (F33:9048, F33:2787) favor volume minimization over conformational restriction.

deep_dives.label: Structural reading L8-L12
deep_dives.caption: Early attention heads read the 6 structural contacts and establish local sequence context. L8 head 6 (-1.63 proj) is a key eraser, while heads at L9-12 integrate information from flanking charged residues (K, E, D, Q). The frequent lead changes in the logit lens reflect the chemical diversity of this information, not model uncertainty.

deep_dives.label: Context features L9-L18
deep_dives.caption: Features F9:5728 (56.7 proj) and F9:1281 (51.9 proj) encode the charged local environment. By L18, features F18:4071 (18.3 proj) and F18:1860 (17.8 proj) represent loop flexibility and secondary structure absence. These features characterize the position's context, not candidate amino acids.

deep_dives.label: Decision onset L24
deep_dives.caption: L24 is where perception becomes decision. F24:5080 (37.2 proj, attention) is the first strongly amino-acid-specific feature, favoring small residues. This marks the transition from 'encoding context' to 'predicting candidates.'

deep_dives.label: MLP competition L28-L31
deep_dives.caption: The decisive MLP competition. L28 provides +6.9 total projection (N28:1320 votes P, N28:1073 votes P>A). L29 contributes -0.38 (mixed votes). L30 adds +2.1 (N30:4443 votes R/T/P). L31 delivers +5.8 (N31:5095 votes A>P with 1.20 proj for P). Proline peaks at L31 but loses to alanine's sustained support.

deep_dives.label: Valine surge L27-L29
deep_dives.caption: Valine's dramatic rise and fall. L27 MLP contributes +1.5 for valine. L28 MLP adds +6.9 total (hydrophobic neurons fire). But L28 attention head 8 (+1.96 structural writer) and L29 head 18 (-1.71 structural eraser) revise the structural interpretation, and valine collapses from 40% to 28% to 8%.

deep_dives.label: Final decision L33
deep_dives.caption: Final-layer features F33:9048 (81.3 proj), F33:2787 (74.1 proj), and F33:6423 (71.4 proj) encode the model's ultimate interpretation: 'small side chain' (favoring A, S) over 'backbone constraint' (favoring P). These features determine why alanine wins despite proline's strong L28-L31 support.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly identifies position 38 as requiring a small, flexible residue in a loop environment with mixed local chemistry and no co-evolutionary constraints. However, it misinterprets 'small and flexible' as 'minimal side chain volume' rather than 'backbone conformational constraint.' Alanine wins at 43% because the most active final-layer features (F33:9048, F33:2787) favor volume minimization, while proline's cyclic backbone—the actual structural requirement—is underweighted. The decisive evidence is in L28-L32 MLP neurons: proline-specific neurons fire strongly (N28:1320, N31:5095), but alanine receives more sustained support across all final layers. The model's error stems from emphasizing side-chain size over backbone geometry, a subtle distinction that requires recognizing proline's unique conformational role in loops.
